Logging is usually not a dependency.  It&#39;s not *required* for the object&#39;s
functionality.  It&#39;s merely a *notification* about what the object is doing.

--Nat

On 07/11/2007, Stephen Smith &lt;steve@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;   Use the Dependency Injection pattern to inject your Logger into your
&gt; class, and then use JMock or a similar mocking API
&gt; to assert that the logger is called with your expected parameters.
&gt;
&gt; ---
&gt; Stephen Smith, MEng (Wales).
&gt; http://www.stephen-smith.co.uk/
&gt;
&gt; Nat Pryce wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I prefer to separate the notification of significant events from the
&gt; logging
&gt; &gt; (or other handling) of those events. It&#39;s easy to test the notification
&gt; &gt; with mock objects and then wire the notifications into a logging system
&gt; in
&gt; &gt; the production system.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; More info about doing this (in C#) at
&gt; &gt; http://nat.truemesh.com/archives/000488.html.
&gt; &gt; &lt;http://nat.truemesh.com/archives/000488.html.&gt;
&gt; &gt; And an easy way to implement notifications in Java at
